Data Cleaning

Although my dataset came fairly complete and mostly tidy from the source, it lacked important metadata about each variable as it was stored in a .csv file. My cleaning of the data involved going through the dataset to find variables which would be useful to convert to into factors, logicals, and datetimes. To do so I used a series of for loops inspired by L11 Exercise 10.

My progress

To begin my EDA, I borrowed code from L11 Exercise 9 to generate quick bar charts and histograms to visualize the distributions of all factor and numerical variables. My research question from the first progress memo was investigating the primary predictors of traffic incidents in Chicago, which I did not realize was recorded as a variable already in the dataset. Below are very rough barplots of the distribution of the primary and secondary contributory causes of crashes in the dataset:

Seeing that the primary and secondary contributory causes recorded in this dataset were either not-applicable or undetermined was quite unsatisfying. The lack of unexpected results was a trend found in the distribution of lighting conditions, road defects, and most severe injury.

Such plots reveal that most crashes, fortunately, do not appear to be due to extreme weather or road conditions, and most are not incredibly serious.

Thus, I would like to change the direction of my EDA from this point onwards into investigating the primary predictors of particular intensities of crashes, based on the most_severe_injury plot above, and particular types of crashes, based upon the prim_contributory_cause plot. For example, what conditions correlate with crashes due to a failure to reduce vehicle speed? How intense, typically are these kinds of crashes? Viewing the dataset with a more specific lense may help me develop more concrete findings. One particular direction I can envision myself taking this project is looking solely at âfailure to yield right-of-wayâ crashes. Such crashes might be due to an inability to see an oncoming car or pedestrian, and as I will be integrating map data into this project, I may be able to find certain areas where these types of crashes are concentrated, which could elucidate design faults in the roads at these areas.

Other Interesting Findings

The only two datetime variables in this dataset record when a crash occurs and when it is reported to police, so I thought it would be interesting to subtract the two and look at delay trends. I found that within each unit of time (within a day, week, year, two years, etc.) delays are concentrated towards the beginning of that period of time, shown by the right-skewness of the plots below. However, if one looks more closely at longer periods of time, there is a curious grouping pattern which reveals that crashes are reported at âroundâ intervals of time (1 complete day, 2 complete days, 1 complete year, etc.) after the crash. This is particularly evident in the middle plot which shows the distribution of reporting delays throughout the week.

Next Steps

My next steps are to look closer at multivariate analyses using the guiding question presented above and to work on mapping the data using the tigris package as I mentioned in the first memo. My guiding question for the multivariate analyses will be what are the best predictors of different severities and types of crashes, based on the most_severe_injury_distribution shown above.

I will spend some time over Thanksgiving Break to join the tigris data with crashes which have recorded longitudes and latitudes, and then spend reading week fine-tuning my key visualizations and the final presentation of my work. I intend to make the early-submission deadline.
